**Machine Learning Project: Loan Amount & Loan**
Status Prediction
I successfully completed an end-to-end Machine Learning project that demonstrates how a single dataset
can be used to solve two different prediction problems. The objective was to predict the Loan Amount
(Regression) and determine the Loan Status (Classification). This project provided valuable experience in
applying multiple machine learning techniques, comparing model performance, and selecting the most
suitable algorithm for each task.
Project Workflow
Step 1: Data Exploration
• Loaded the loan dataset using Pandas.
• Performed Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) to understand feature distributions.
• Examined summary statistics and identified missing values.
• Visualized numerical and categorical features using histograms, boxplots, and count plots.

Step 2: Data Preprocessing
• Treated missing values using appropriate imputation techniques.
• Encoded categorical variables into numerical representations.
• Checked for duplicate records and inconsistent values.
• Prepared the dataset for machine learning by separating features and target variables.

Step 3: Train-Test Split
• Split the dataset into 80% training and 20% testing data.
• Used a fixed random state to ensure reproducible results.

Step 4: Regression Model
The first objective was to predict the Loan Amount, which is a continuous numerical value.
Model Used
• Linear Regression
Performance

• MAE: 16.6568
• RMSE: 30.061
• R² Score: 0.7938
• Adjusted R²: 0.7799

1   The model explained approximately 79% of the variance in loan amounts, indicating strong predictive
performance for a baseline regression model.

Step 5: Classification Models
The second objective was to predict whether a loan application would be Approved or Rejected.
Models Compared
• Logistic Regression
• Support Vector Classifier (SVC)


Model Comparison
Logistic Regression
• Accuracy: 79.83%
• Precision: 81.89%
• Recall: 79.83%
• F1-Score: 77.60%
• AUC: 0.7519

Support Vector Classifier
• Accuracy: 78.99%
• Precision: 81.19%
• Recall: 78.99%
• F1-Score: 76.49%
• AUC: 0.7199

Among the classification models, Logistic Regression delivered the best overall performance by achieving
higher Accuracy, F1-Score, and AUC than SVC.
Key Findings
• Applicant income, loan history, and financial attributes played a significant role in predicting both
loan amount and loan approval.
• Proper preprocessing and feature encoding substantially improved model performance.
• Linear Regression proved effective for continuous value prediction, while Logistic Regression was the
most suitable classifier for this dataset.

Challenges Faced
• Handling missing values without introducing bias.
• Converting categorical variables into machine-readable formats.
• Selecting appropriate evaluation metrics for regression and classification problems.
• Comparing models fairly using multiple performance measures.

2  What I Learned
This project strengthened my understanding of the complete machine learning lifecycle, including data
cleaning, feature engineering, model training, evaluation, and interpretation. One of the biggest takeaways
was that the quality of data preprocessing often has a greater impact on model performance than
choosing a more complex algorithm. I also learned the importance of selecting evaluation metrics based
on the problem type—R² and RMSE for regression, and Accuracy, Precision, Recall, F1-Score, and AUC for
classification.

Overall, this project enhanced my practical skills in applying machine learning to real-world financial data
and reinforced the importance of building interpretable, well-evaluated predictive models.
